{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bfd0fd9e-df74-4165-9df9-1845a2c8ec19","content":"In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance **per HTTP request** — each request gets its own scope. In MAUI, there are no HTTP requests. The app has **one long-lived scope** for its entire lifetime, so `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton`. Your DbContext is reused everywhere.\n\n**Fixes:**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient`** — simplest option. You get a fresh DbContext each time one is injected:\n   ```csharp\n   builder.Services.AddTransient<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n\n2. **Create manual scopes** — if you need scoped lifetime control, inject `IServiceScopeFactory` and create scopes yourself:\n   ```csharp\n   using var scope = scopeFactory.CreateScope();\n   var db = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n\n`AddTransient` is usually the right call for DbContext in MAUI.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a0703c21-ba0d-419e-b4d3-75cd7c2cf6d5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common pitfall when migrating from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scoping — specifically why `AddScoped` behaves differently in MAUI than in ASP.NET Core.\n\nThis is a conceptual question I can answer directly without needing to search any codebase.\n\nIn ASP.NET Core, a \"scope\" is created per HTTP request, so `AddScoped` gives you a new instance per request. In MAUI, there's no concept of an HTTP request — the app has a single scope for its entire lifetime. So `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton`, meaning your DbContext is reused across all page navigations.\n\n\nThe workaround is straightforward: either switch to `AddTransient` to get a fresh DbContext on each injection, or use `IServiceScopeFactory` to manually create and manage scopes when you need them.","outputTokens":453},"id":"5ad2683e-aa21-47ca-a811-3f38b5542f3c","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:42:14.958Z","parentId":"7b6c7be7-693c-4016-8b3d-6a67b58af64b"}
